# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andrew-carnegie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] As in the previous decade, emphasis remained on the back of the skirt, with fullness gradually rising from behind the knees to just below the waist.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The fullness in back was balanced by a fuller, lower chest, achieved by rigid corseting, creating an S-shaped silhouette, foreshadowing the more radical form of this shape that would become popular in the early 1900s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] These gowns typically did not have a long train in the back, which was different from the gowns worn in the 1870s, and were extremely tight.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] They were known as the "hobble-skirt" due to the tightness of them.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Winter gowns were made in darker hues whereas summer ones were made in lighter colors.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Velvet was also a very popular fabric used during this period.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Skirts were looped, draped, or tied up in various ways, and worn over matching or contrasting colored underskirts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The *polonaise* was a revival style based on a fashion of the 1780s, with a fitted, cutaway overdress caught up and draped over an underskirt.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Long, jacket-like fitted bodices called basques were also popular for clothing during the day.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Gowns were sleeveless and low-necked (except for matrons), and were worn with long over the elbow or shoulder length gloves of fine kidskin or suede.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Choker necklaces and jewelled collars were fashionable under the influence of Alexandra, Princess of Wales, who wore this fashion to disguise a scar on her neck.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The bustle returned to fashion and reached its greatest proportions c.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] 1886–1888, extending almost straight out from the back waist to support a profusion of drapery, frills, swags, and ribbons.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The fashionable corset created a low, full bust with little separation of the breasts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] A usual type of undergarment was called *combinations*, a camisole with attached knee- or calf-length drawers, worn under the corset, bustle, and petticoat.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Woolen combinations were recommended for health, especially when engaging in fashionable sports.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Riding habits had become a "uniform" of matching jacket and skirt worn with a high-collared shirt or chemisette, with a top hat and veil.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] They were worn without bustles, but the cut of the jacket followed the silhouette of the day.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] In contrast, hunting costumes were far more fashionably styled, with draped ankle-length skirts worn with boots or gaiters.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Tailored costumes consisting of a long jacket and skirt were worn for travel or walking; these were worn with the bustle and a small hat or bonnet.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Travelers wore long coats like dusters to protect their clothes from dirt, rain, and soot.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Artistic dress remained an undercurrent in Bohemian circles throughout the 1880s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] In reaction to the heavy drapery and rigid corseting of mainstream Paris fashion, aesthetic dress focused on beautiful fabrics made up simply, sometimes loosely fitted or with a belt at the waist.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Aesthetic ideas influenced the tea gown, a frothy confection increasingly worn in the home, even to receive visitors.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Hair was usually pulled back at the sides and worn in a low knot or cluster of ringlets; later hair was swept up to the top of the head.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Bonnets resembled hats except for their ribbons tied under the chin; both had curvy brims.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Sketch of an extremely modish tennis costume.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Georgiana Burne-Jones wears a princess-line gown trimmed with ruched panels and ruffles, c.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] August 1882 fashion plate shows the return of the bustle: the tight overdress is looped up behind.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Whistler's Portrait of Lady Meux (1881–1882) shows the fashionable full bosom.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Misses' Polonaise has fitted bodice with a low point in front.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The front of the skirt is cutaway and the back is looped up after the fashion of the 1780s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] It is shown over a gored skirt with ruffles.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Throughout the century, younger teenage girls ("misses" in fashion plates) wore their skirts just above their ankles.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Bathing dresses of 1883 show fashionable rear fullness.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The bodice is draped up at both sides and worn over a matching underskirt.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Madame Paul Poirson wears the fashionable neckline of mid-decade, wide at the bust and narrower at the shoulder.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Flowers trim her bodice, hair, and draped skirt, 1885.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Outfit which is both strongly influenced by menswear and bustled.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Elbow-length gloves meet the shorter sleeves.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] "Woman with a fan made of feathers", photograph by Alvan S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Hairstyle of 1887 is swept up into a knot, with the front hair curled and frizzled over the forehead.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Fashions from *La Mode Illustrée* show dresses made of contrasting fabrics worn with "shelf" bustles and opera-length gloves, 1887.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Princess Alix of Hesse wears a high-necked day dress, 1887.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Fashions of 1888 feature full busts, large "shelf" bustles, and wide shoulders.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Gloves reach the elbow or slightly above.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Eleanora Iselin wears a high-necked black satin costume trimmed with beaded passementerie, 1888.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Vicomtesse De Montmorand wears a gown fastened in back, without a bustle, signalling the styles of the next decade.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Her hair is twisted into a small knot on top of her head and is worn with a curly fringe or bangs, 1889.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Japanese print showing two young ladies dressed according to the latest Western fashions of time — except that the colors and designs of the fabrics are to Japanese tastes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Three piece suits, "ditto suits", consisting of a sack coat with matching waistcoat (U.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] *vest*) and trousers (called in the UK a "lounge suit") continued as an informal alternative to the contrasting frock coat, waistcoat and trousers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The cutaway morning coat was still worn for formal day occasions in Europe and major cities elsewhere, with a dress shirt and an ascot tie.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The most formal evening dress remained a dark tail coat and trousers with a dark waistcoat.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Evening wear was worn with a white bow tie and a shirt with a winged collar.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] In mid-decade, a more relaxed formal coat appeared: the dinner jacket or tuxedo, which featured a shawl collar with silk or satin facings, and one or two buttons.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Dinner jackets were appropriate when "dressing for dinner" at home or at a men's club.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The Norfolk jacket was popular for shooting and rugged outdoor pursuits.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] It was made of sturdy tweed or similar fabric and featured paired box pleats over the chest and back, with a fabric belt.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Full-length trousers were worn for most occasions; tweed or woollen breeches were worn for hunting and other outdoor pursuits.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Knee-length topcoats, often with contrasting velvet or fur collars, and calf-length overcoats were worn in winter.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] By the 1880s the majority of the working class, even shepherds, adopted jackets and waistcoats in fustian and corduroy with corduroy trousers, giving up their smock frocks.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Shirt collars were turned over or pressed into "wings".
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Dress shirts had stiff fronts, sometimes decorated with shirt studs, and buttoned up the back.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] The usual necktie was the four-in-hand or the newly fashionable Ascot tie, made up as a neckband with wide wings attached and worn with a stickpin.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Narrow ribbon ties were tied in a bow, and the white bowtie was worn with formal evening wear.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] As in the 1870s, top hats remained a requirement for upper class formal wear; bowlers and soft felt hats in a variety of shapes were worn for more casual occasions, and flat straw boaters were worn for yachting and other nautical pastimes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Shoes of the 1880s had higher heels and a narrow toe.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Painter John Singer Sargent wears a formally pleated Ascot tie.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] His shirt collar has softly curled wings, c.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Hermann von Helmholtz wears a dark coat, waistcoat, and trousers with a stiff-fronted and stiff-collared shirt, German, 1881.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Theodor Mommsen wears a narrow necktie tied in a bow with his dark suit, German, 1881.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] *Vanity Fair* sketch of agricultural scientist John Bennet Lawes portrays him in walking clothes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] His coat with a waist seam and skirts cutaway in a smooth curve is worn with matching trousers and collared waistcoat, 1882.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] George Etiene Cartier wears a dark frock coat, a decorative double-breasted waistcoat, and a narrow bow tie.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Lawmen of Dodge City wear their coats with only the high top button fastened.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Wyatt Earp (front row, second from left) wears a three-piece "ditto" suit with contrasting binding around the coat collar and lapel, 1883.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Composer Anton Rubinstein conducts in formal evening wear (dark coat, trousers, and waistcoat, white shirt and tie), 1887.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Young girls wore dresses with round collars and sashes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] When going out, especially in the winter, girls wore many layers to keep warm.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] A warm coat was worn with kid leather gloves.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Gloves were worn under a muff hand warmer, so when the girl removed her hands from the muff, her gloves would keep them warm.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Just like ladies, all upper-class Victorian girls wore gloves when going out.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] A hat or bonnet was worn as well, along with long, knee-length button-up boots or shorter boots with gaiters to give the appearance of wearing long boots.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1880s-in-western-fashion] Older boys wore knee-length breeches and jackets with round-collared shirts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The **1891 New Orleans lynchings** were the murders of 11 Italian Americans, immigrants in New Orleans, by a mob for their alleged role in the murder of police chief David Hennessy after some of them had been acquitted at trial.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] It was the largest single mass lynching in American history.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Most of the lynching victims accused in the murder had been rounded up and charged due to their Italian ethnicity.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The lynching took place on March 14, the day after the trial of nine of the nineteen men indicted in Hennessy's murder.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Six of these defendants were acquitted, and a mistrial was declared for the remaining three because the jury failed to agree on their verdicts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] There was a widespread belief in the city that Italian American organized crime was responsible for the killing of the police chief in a period of anti-Italian sentiment and rising crime.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Italian American voters were also known to prefer the scandal-plagued city political machine to the new Reform Democrat mayor, whose own role in inciting the violence that followed may well have been an attempt to misuse government power for the repression of his political opponents.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Believing the jury had been fixed by organized crime, a mob broke into the jail where the men were being held and killed eleven of the prisoners, most by shooting.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The mob outside the jail numbered in the thousands and included some of the city's most prominent citizens.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The incident had serious national repercussions.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The Italian consul Pasquale Corte in New Orleans registered a protest and left the city in May 1891 at his government's direction.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The *New York Times* published a lengthy statement charging city politicians with responsibility for the lynching of the Italians.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Italy cut off diplomatic relations with the United States, sparking rumors of war.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Increased anti-Italian sentiment led to calls for restrictions on immigration.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The word "Mafia" entered the American lexicon, and this incident increased awareness of the Italian mafioso, establishing it in the popular imagination of Americans.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The lynchings were the subject of the 1999 HBO film *Vendetta*, starring Christopher Walken.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The film is based on a 1977 history book of the same name by Richard Gambino.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In late 19th-century America, there was a growing number of Italians who had been brought in by the business community to replace black labor.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Sugar planters, in particular, sought workers who were more efficient than formerly enslaved people; they hired immigrant recruiters to bring Italians to southern Louisiana.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In the 1890s, thousands of Italians were arriving in New Orleans each year.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Many settled in the French Quarter, which by the early 20th century had a section known as "Little Sicily." Furthermore, during the whole of the 19th century and well into the 20th, Italian immigrants to the United States were often referred to as "White niggers".
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In a letter responding to an inquiry about immigration in New Orleans, Mayor Joseph A.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] According to professor of history Humbert Nelli, Mayor Shakspeare had been elected as a Reform Democrat with the backing of the Louisiana Republican Party, which had grown increasingly powerless following the end of the Reconstruction era.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Mayor Shakspeare and the Republicans were united in opposition to the city's corrupt and scandal-plagued political machine, which was called the Regular Democratic Organization, and remained firmly supported by the city's Italian-American voters.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] According to Nelli, this may well have been the real reason for the mayor's outspoken anti-Italianism.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] On the evening of October 15, 1890, New Orleans police chief David Hennessy was shot by several gunmen as he walked home from work.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Hennessy returned fire and chased his attackers before collapsing.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] When asked who had shot him, Hennessy reportedly whispered to Captain William O'Connor, "dagos" (a derogatory term for Italians and others of Mediterranean heritage).
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Hennessy was awake in the hospital for several hours after the shooting and spoke to friends but did not name the shooters.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The next day complications set in, and he died.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] There had been an ongoing feud between the Provenzano and Matranga families, who were business rivals on the New Orleans waterfront.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Hennessy had put several of the Provenzanos in prison, and their appeal trial was coming up.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] According to some reports, Hennessy had been planning to offer new evidence at the trial that would clear the Provenzanos and implicate the Matrangas.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] If true, this would mean that the Matrangas, and not the Provenzanos, had a motive for the murder.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] A policeman who was a friend of Hennessy's later testified that Hennessy had told him he had no such plans.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In any case, it was widely believed that Hennessy's killers were Italian.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Local papers such as the *Times-Democrat* and the *Daily Picayune* freely blamed "Dagoes" for the murder.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The murder was quickly followed by mass arrests of local Italians.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Shakspeare (according to the *Picayune*) told the police to "scour the whole neighborhood.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Arrest every Italian you come across." Within 24 hours, 45 people had been arrested.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] By some accounts, as many as 250 Italians were rounded up.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Most were eventually released for lack of evidence.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Local Italians were afraid to leave their homes for several days after the murder, but eventually the furor died down and they returned to work.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Nineteen men were ultimately charged with the murder or as accessories and held without bail in the parish prison.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] These included Charles Matranga, who was charged with plotting the murder, and several of the Matrangas' friends and workers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Pietro Monasterio, a shoemaker, was arrested because he lived across the street from where Hennessy was standing when he was shot.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] On October 23, the committee published an open letter to the Italian community encouraging them to expose the criminals amongst them anonymously.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The letter was signed by the committee's chairman, Edgar H.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Farrar, who later served as president of the American Bar Association.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Other prominent members of the Committee included General Algernon S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Flower, Colonel James Lewis, and architect Thomas Sully.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The Committee of Fifty hired two private detectives to pose as prisoners and try to get the defendants to talk about the murder.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Apparently the detectives did not obtain any useful information, because they were not asked to testify at the trial.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Only Polizzi, who appeared to be mentally ill, said anything to incriminate himself, and his confession was deemed inadmissible.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Meanwhile, the defendants were subject to extremely negative pretrial publicity.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Several shotguns were found near the scene of the crime.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] One was a muzzle-loading shotgun of a type which was widely used throughout the American South but which the New Orleans Police Department claimed was a lupara, a "favorite" weapon of the Sicilian Mafia.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Another shotgun found at the scene had a hinged stock.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Local newspapers alleged that the guns were imported from Sicily; in reality, they had been manufactured by the W.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Spurred to action by the popular accounts of Hennessy's murder, a 29-year-old newspaper salesman named Thomas Duffy walked into the prison on October 17, 1890, sought out Antonio Scaffidi, whom he had heard was a suspect, and shot him in the neck with a revolver.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Scaffidi survived the attack, only to be lynched a few months later.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Duffy was eventually convicted of assault and sentenced to six months in prison.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] A trial for nine of the suspects began on February 16, 1891, and concluded on March 13, 1891, with Judge Joshua G.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The defendants were represented by Lionel Adams of the law firm Adams and O'Malley, and the state was represented by Orleans Parish district attorney Charles A.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Jury selection was a time-consuming process: Hundreds of prospective jurors were rejected before 12 people were found who were not opposed to capital punishment, were not openly prejudiced against Italians, and were not of Italian descent themselves.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Much of the evidence presented at trial was weak or contradictory.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The murder had taken place on a poorly lit street on a damp night in a notoriously corrupt city and the eyewitness testimony was unreliable.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Suspects were identified by witnesses who had not seen their faces but only their clothing.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Captain Bill O'Connor, the witness who claimed to have heard Hennessy blame "Dagoes" for the assassination, was not called to testify.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] There were numerous other discrepancies and improprieties.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] At one point, two employees of the defense law firm were arrested for attempting to bribe prospective jurors.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Afterward, when federal district attorney William Grant looked into the case, he reported that the evidence against the men was "exceedingly unsatisfactory" and inconclusive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] He could find no evidence linking any of the lynched men to the Mafia or to any attempts to bribe the jury.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The bribery charges were eventually dismissed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Matranga and another man, Bastian Incardona, were found not guilty by directed verdict, as no evidence had been presented against them.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The jury declared four of the defendants not guilty, and asked the judge to declare a mistrial for the other three, as they could not agree on a verdict.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The six who were acquitted were not released but were held pending an additional charge of "lying in wait" with intent to commit murder.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Luzenberg admitted that without a murder conviction, he would be forced to drop the "lying in wait" charges.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] But all nineteen men were returned to the prison—a decision which would prove fatal for some of them.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The jurors were given the option to leave by a side door but chose to walk out the front door and face the angry crowd.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Several defended their decision to reporters, arguing that they had "reasonable doubt" and had done what they thought was right.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Some were harassed, threatened, fired from their jobs, and otherwise penalized for failing to convict the Italians.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] A group of about 150 people calling themselves the Committee on Safety (referring to the Revolutionary War era) met that evening to plan their response.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The following morning, an ad appeared in local newspapers calling for a mass meeting at the statue of Henry Clay near the prison.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] As thousands of demonstrators gathered near the Parish Prison, Pasquale Corte, the Italian consul in New Orleans sought the help of Louisiana governor Francis T.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Nicholls to prevent an outbreak of violence.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The governor declined to take any action without a request from Mayor Shakspeare, who had gone out to breakfast and could not be reached.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Meanwhile, at the Clay statue, attorney William S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Lynchings were not uncommon in the United States and the Tuskegee Institute recorded the lynchings of 3,446 blacks and 1,297 whites between 1882 and 1968, with the peak occurring in the 1890s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Inside the prison, as the mob was breaking down the door with a battering ram, prison warden Lemuel Davis let the 19 Italian prisoners out of their cells and told them to hide as best they could.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Although the thousands of demonstrators outside for the lynching were a spontaneous outburst, the killings were carried out by a relatively small, disciplined "execution squad" within the mob led by Parkerson and three other city leaders: Walter Denegre, lawyer; James D.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Houston, politician and businessman; and John C.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Wickliffe, editor of the *New Delta* newspaper.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Other members of the lynch mob included John M.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Parker, who was elected as Louisiana's 37th governor, and Walter C.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Flower, who was elected as the 44th mayor of New Orleans.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The mentally ill Polizzi was hauled outside, hanged from a lamppost, and shot.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Antonio Bagnetto, a fruit peddler, was hanged from a tree and shot.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Nine others were shot or clubbed to death inside the prison.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The bullet-riddled bodies of Polizzi and Bagnetto were left hanging for hours.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The court and district attorney set the survivors free after the lynching and dropped the charges against the men who had not yet been tried.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Only one of the lynching victims, Polizzi, had a police record in the US, having reportedly cut a man with a knife in Austin, Texas, several years earlier.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Two others had police records in Italy: Geraci had been accused of murder and had fled before he could be tried, and Comitis had been convicted of theft.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Incardona was wanted in Italy as a petty criminal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Three of the men—Comitis, Monasterio, and Traina—had not applied for US citizenship and could still be considered Italian subjects.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] All of those lynched were Sicilian immigrants except for Macheca, a Louisiana native of Sicilian descent, and Comitis, who was from Abruzzi.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Most anti-Italianism in the United States was directed at Southern Italians, particularly Sicilians, who were often considered to be more racially suspect.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The US Bureau of Immigration reinforced this distinction, following the Italian practice of classifying Northern and Southern Italians as two different races.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] However, even though on a legal level both Northern and Southern Italians were considered to be white, between 1890 and 1910, Sicilian-Americans made up less than 4 percent of the white male population, yet were roughly 40 percent of the white victims of Southern lynch mobs.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Before that, many white victims were Irish Catholics.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Sicilians in the South often had menial positions, working on construction of levees and railroads and as farm workers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Macheca's personal history, however, is more complex.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] He was born in 1843 to a Sicilian father and Maltese mother in Louisiana and adopted and raised by his mother's second husband, a Maltese man named Macheca (originally Mercieca).
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] During the American Civil War, he served in the Confederate States Army.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In 1868, either Macheca led a group of Sicilians in a violent, anti-black demonstration.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Although not a member of the White League, as a Captain of the 1st Louisiana Infantry Regiment, Macheca fought in the Battle of Liberty Place on the same side as the Crescent City White League in 1874.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Macheca was also the leader of a crew of Sicilian immigrants called "The Innocents".
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Depending on the source, "The Innocents" were either a White Supremacist street gang employed by the Regular Democratic Organization to commit voter intimidation and murder, the beginning of the New Orleans crime family, or security guards hired to protect Macheca and his various businesses.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The racial politics are further complicated by the involvement in the 1891 riot of a large number of African-American lynchers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] For example, Colonel James Lewis, a member of the elite Committee of Fifty, was a mixed-race African-American man who had been an officer in the Louisiana Native Guard and leader of the New Orleans Republican Party.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In fact, Lewis was one of the signatories of a letter to the Italian community, urging people to inform the Committee of Fifty about the suspects and threatening extrajudicial action.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] American newspaper accounts at the time were largely sympathetic to the lynchers and anti-Italian in tone.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The victims were presumed to have been involved with the Mafia, a criminal organization that dealt in theft, terror and murder, and therefore deserving of their fate.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Many commentators offered a *pro forma* condemnation of vigilantism before ultimately blaming the victims and defending the lynchers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Massachusetts representative Henry Cabot Lodge, for example, claimed to deplore the mob's behavior and then proceeded to justify it while proposing new restrictions on Italian immigration.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Even the *London Times* expressed approval.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Not all editors were convinced of the mob's innocence.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The *Charleston News and Courier* argued that murder by vigilantes was no more acceptable than any other kind.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Louis Republic* wrote that the men were killed "on proof of being 'dagoes' and on the merest suspicion of being guilty of any other crime." Some Northern newspapers also condemned the lynchings.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Many others, however, implicitly or explicitly condoned them.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] A *Boston Globe* front-page headline read, "STILETTO RULE: New Orleans Arose to Meet the Curse." Boston was another industrial city that had been receiving many immigrants from Southern Italy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Following strong protests by the Italian government and the Italian-American community, the press eventually became less supportive of the lynchers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] A grand jury convened on March 17, 1891, to investigate the lynching.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Marr, who presided over the jury, was a longtime personal friend of several of the lynch mob participants.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] On May 5, 1891, the grand jury published a report concluding that several jurors in the Hennessy case had been bribed to acquit the Italians.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Yet, no proof was offered and no criminal charges were pursued.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The grand jury claimed that it could not identify the participants in the lynching.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In the same report, the lynching was described as a "gathering" of "several thousands of the first, best, and even the most law-abiding, of the citizens of this city." No one was indicted.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Only Thomas Duffy, the newspaper salesman who had shot Scaffidi in October, was penalized.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Duffy was serving time in the parish prison at the time of the lynching.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] After the Hennessy case, at least eight more men of Italian descent were lynched in Louisiana during the 1890s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In each case, as was typical of lynchings, local authorities claimed to be unable to identify anyone involved and never prosecuted anyone for the murders.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The incident strained relations between the United States and Italy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The Italian consul Pasquale Corte left New Orleans in late May 1891 and the *New York Times* published his statement accusing the city politicians of responsibility for the lynchings.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The Italian government demanded that the lynch mob be brought to justice and that reparations be paid to the dead men's families.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] When the US declined to prosecute the mob leaders, Italy recalled its ambassador from Washington in protest.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The US followed suit, recalling its legation from Rome.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Diplomatic relations remained at an impasse for over a year, and there were rumors of a declaration of war on America as a result of the murders.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] As part of a wider effort to ease tensions with Italy and placate Italian Americans, President Benjamin Harrison declared the first nationwide celebration of Columbus Day in 1892, commemorating the 400th anniversary of the Italian explorer's landing in the New World.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The contrasting American and Italian attitudes toward the lynchings are perhaps best summarized by Theodore Roosevelt's comment.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The incident has been mostly forgotten in the US, relegated to the footnotes of American history texts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] However, it is more widely known in Italy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Mayor Shakspeare was narrowly defeated for reelection in 1892 by Regular Democratic Organization candidate John Fitzpatrick.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The Italian-American vote, which remained even more firmly on the political machine's side for decades after the lynchings, was a decisive factor in Mayor Shakspeare's defeat.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Gaspare Marchesi, the boy who survived by hiding in the prison while his father was lynched, was awarded $5,000 in damages in 1893 after successfully suing the city of New Orleans.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The death of Hennessy became a rallying cry for law enforcement and nativists to halt the immigration of Italians into America.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In an influential essay, Henry Cabot Lodge pointed out that "the paupers and criminals of Europe" were "pouring into the United States" and proposed a literacy test to weed out the least desirable immigrants.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The Hennessy case introduced the word "Mafia" to the American public.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] It first made widely known the now-familiar image of the Italian-American mafioso.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Journalists of the time used the word "Mafia" loosely to sell newspapers, often linking the crimes of individual Italians to organized crime when no evidence of such a connection existed for that particular crime.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] After the lynching, newspapers circulated wild rumors that thousands of Italian Americans were plotting to attack New Orleans and were wrecking railroads in New York and Chicago.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The press reported that the defense lawyers in the Hennessy case were paid by the Mafia when Italian-language newspapers in cities across the country had raised funds for the men's legal defense.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Soon historians were applying the "Mafia" label retroactively to crimes committed by Italians in the past.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In the 1970s, two studies by Italian American historians challenged the prevailing view.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Humbert Nelli, a professor of history at the University of Kentucky, examined the Hennessy case in a chapter of *The Business of Crime* (1976).
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Nelli demonstrated that the evidence against the defendants was weak and argued that the murder was too poorly planned and amateurish to have been a Mafia hit.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In a chapter on crime in New Orleans, he claims that although crime flourished among the city's Southern Italians at the time, it could not accurately be attributed to *mafiosi*.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In *Vendetta: The True Story of the Largest Lynching in U.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] History* (1977), Richard Gambino, a professor at City University of New York, raised numerous questions about the investigation and trial and proposes an alternative theory about Hennessy's murder.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Among other things, Gambino notes that Hennessy had a "colorful" past that provided any number of possible motives to be subject to murder, none of which the police chose to investigate.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] He also notes that shortly after the lynching, the city passed an ordinance giving control of all New Orleans dock work to the newly formed Louisiana Construction and Improvement Corporation, a business headed by several of the lynch mob leaders.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Italian waterfront merchants and workers, who had been making remarkable economic progress up to then, were thus eliminated as competitors.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The 1999 HBO movie *Vendetta*, starring Christopher Walken and directed by Nicholas Meyer, is based on Gambino's book.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] It portrays Macheca and several of the other lynched men as innocent victims.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] It is narrated by the character of Gaspare Marchesi, the boy who escaped being lynched by hiding in the prison.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Reviewers have criticized Gambino's language as sensational and partisan while acknowledging the book's merits.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Writing in the *Journal of American History* in 1977, Raymond Nussbaum (an alumnus of Tulane University) suggested that historians looking for a balanced account of the lynching look elsewhere.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] In a film review that appeared in the same journal in 2000, Clive Webb calls the movie a "compelling portrait of prejudice" and recommends that historians consult the book for more information.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] The lynching is discussed in the 2004 documentary, *Linciati: Lynchings of Italians in America*, directed by M.
[src:andrew-carnegie/1891-new-orleans-lynchings] Lynchings of Italians are also mentioned in various documentaries on the Italian-American experience.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:andrew-carnegie/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] The **3M computer** industrial goal was first proposed in the early 1980s by Raj Reddy and his colleagues at Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) as a minimum specification for academic and technical workstations.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] It requires at least one megabyte of memory, a one megapixel display with 1024×1024 1-bit pixels, and one million instructions per second (MIPS) of processing power.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] It was also often said that it should cost no more than one "megapenny" or $10,000 (equivalent to $39,000 in 2025).
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] At that time, a typical desktop computer such as an early IBM Personal Computer might have 1/8 of a megabyte of memory (128K), 1/4 of a million pixels (640 × 400 monochrome display), and run at 1/3 million instructions per second (5 MHz 8088).
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] The concept was inspired by the Xerox Alto which had been designed in the 1970s at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] Several Alto workstations were donated to CMU, Stanford, and MIT in 1979.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] An early 3M computer is the PERQ Workstation made by Three Rivers Computer Corporation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] It has a 1 million P-codes (Pascal instructions) per second processor, 256 KB of RAM (upgradeable to 1 MB), and a 768×1024 pixel display on a 15-inch (380 mm) display.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] Though not quite a true 3M machine, it was used as the initial 3M machine for the CMU Scientific Personal Integrated Computing Environment (SPICE) workstation project.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] The Stanford University Network SUN workstation, designed by Andy Bechtolsheim in 1980, is another example.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] It was then commercialized by Sun Microsystems in 1982.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] Apollo Computer (in the Route 128 region) announced the Apollo/Domain computer in 1981.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] By 1986, CMU stated that it expected at least two companies to introduce 3M computers by the end of the year, with academic pricing of $3,000 and retail pricing of $5,000, and Stanford University planned to deploy them in computer labs.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] The first "megapenny" 3M workstation was the Sun-2/50 diskless desktop workstation with a list price of $8,900 in 1986.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] The original NeXT Computer was introduced in 1988 as a 3M machine by Steve Jobs, who first heard this term at Brown University.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] The NeXT MegaPixel Display has just over 930,000 pixels with 2 bits per pixel.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] However, floating-point performance, powered with the Motorola 68882 FPU is only about 0.25 megaflops.
[src:andrew-carnegie/3m-computer] Modern desktop computers exceed the 3M memory and speed requirements by many thousands of times, however 1080p screen pixels are only 2 times larger and 4K 8 times larger, but they are full color so each pixel uses at least 24 times as many bits.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The borough of Manhattan in New York City contains 214 numbered east–west streets ranging from 1st to 228th, the majority of them designated in the Commissioners' Plan of 1811.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] These streets do not run exactly east–west, because the grid plan is aligned with the Hudson River, rather than with the cardinal directions.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Thus, the majority of the Manhattan grid's "west" is approximately 29 degrees north of true west; the angle differs above 155th Street, where the grid initially ended.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The grid now covers the length of the island from 14th Street north.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] All numbered streets carry an East or West prefix – for example, East 10th Street or West 10th Street – which is demarcated at Broadway below 8th Street, and at Fifth Avenue at 8th Street and above.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The numbered streets carry crosstown traffic.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] In general, but with numerous exceptions, even-numbered streets are one-way eastbound and odd-numbered streets are one-way westbound.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Most wider streets, and a few of the narrow ones, carry two-way traffic.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Although the numbered streets begin just north of East Houston Street in the East Village, they generally do not extend west into Greenwich Village, which already had established, named streets when the grid plan was laid out by the Commissioners' Plan of 1811.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Some streets in that area that do continue farther west change direction before reaching the Hudson River.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The highest numbered street on Manhattan Island is 220th Street, but Marble Hill is also within the borough of Manhattan, so the highest street number in the borough is 228th Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The numbering system continues in the Bronx, up to 263rd Street, though east of Van Cortlandt Park the system ends at 243rd Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The lowest numbered street in Manhattan is East 1st Street, which runs through Alphabet City near East Houston Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] There are also three streets numbered as First, Second and Third Place in Battery Park City.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] East 1st Street begins just north of East Houston Street at Avenue A and continues to the Bowery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Peretz Square, a small triangular sliver park where Houston Street, First Street and First Avenue meet marks the spot where the grid takes hold.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] East 2nd Street begins just north of East Houston Street at Avenue C and also continues to the Bowery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The east end of East 3rd, 4th, 5th, and 7th streets is Avenue D, with East 6th Street continuing further eastward and connecting to the FDR Drive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The west end of most of these streets is the Bowery and Third Avenue, except for 3rd Street (formerly Amity Place), which continues to Sixth Avenue; and 4th Street, which extends west and then north to 13th Street in Greenwich Village.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Great Jones Street connects East 3rd to West 3rd.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] East 5th Street goes west to Cooper Square, but is interrupted between Avenues B and C by The Earth School and Public School 364, and between First Avenue and Avenue A by the Village View Apartments.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] East 6th Street contains many Indian restaurants between First and Second Avenues and is sometimes known as Curry Row.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 8th and 9th streets run parallel to each other, beginning at Avenue D, interrupted by Tompkins Square Park at Avenue B, resuming at Avenue A and continuing to Sixth Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] West 8th Street is an important local shopping street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 8th Street between Avenue A and Third Avenue is called St Mark's Place, but it is counted in the length below.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The M8 bus route operates eastbound on 8th Street and westbound on 9th Street between Avenue A and Sixth Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 8th Street has one subway station: Eighth Street–New York University, served by the N, R and W Trains.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Amos, Hammond, and Troy Streets were in the Greenwich Village street grid before 1811.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] In the middle 19th century they were renamed as the western parts of West 10th, 11th and 12th Streets, respectively.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Additionally, **Little West 12th Street** runs parallel to West 13th Street from West Street to the northeast corner of Ninth Avenue and Gansevoort Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 14th Street is a main numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It begins at Avenue C and ends at West Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] From Avenue A or Avenue C to West Street there is service M14A/D bus.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] At 6th Avenue, there is a PATH stop with service to Midtown Manhattan and New Jersey.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Traffic on 15th Street moves from east to west.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The street formerly started at the FDR Drive, but most of the street between the Drive and Avenue C was permanently closed, as was the 15th Street exit from the Drive, after the September 11 attacks, due to the presence of the Con Edison East River Generating Station there.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Only Con Edison personnel have access to the closed portion.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The street is then interrupted by Stuyvesant Town from Avenue C to First Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It then continues to Union Square East (Park Avenue South) where it is interrupted by Union Square It picks up again at Union Square West, and continues unimpeded to Eleventh Avenue at the Hudson River.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Traffic on 16th Street moves from west to east.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It starts at Eleventh Avenue at the Hudson River, and runs until it is interrupted at Union Square West (Broadway) by Union Square.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It picks up again on the other side of the park at Union Square East (Park Avenue South), but is shortly stopped again by Stuyvesant Square from between Second and Third Avenues (Rutherford Place) to between First and Second Avenues (Perlman Place).
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] At First Avenue, it is interrupted by Stuyvesant Town, and starts up again at Avenue C.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It then dead ends between that avenue and the FDR Drive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 17th, 18th and 19th streets start at First Avenue and finish at Eleventh Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It forms the northern borders of both Union Square (between Broadway and Park Avenue South) and Stuyvesant Square.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Composer Antonín Dvořák's New York home was located at 327 East 17th Street, near Perlman Place.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The house was razed by Beth Israel Medical Center after it received approval of a 1991 application to demolish the house and replace it with an AIDS hospice with financing from the photographer Robert Mapplethorpe.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] *Time* Magazine was started at 141 East 17th Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 18th Street has a local subway station at the crossing with Seventh Avenue, served by the 1 (and the 2 at late nights) on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] There used to be an 18th Street station on the IRT Lexington Avenue Line at the crossing with Park Avenue South.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] This street is home to the IAC Building, designed by Frank Gehry.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 19th Street travels west for most of its length, except between Tenth and Eleventh Avenues the travel direction is reversed and traffic flows east.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 20th Street starts at Avenue C, and 21st and 22nd Streets begin at First Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Travel on the last block of the 20th, 21st, and 22nd streets, between Tenth and Eleventh Avenues, is in the opposite direction than it is on the rest of the respective street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 20th Street is very wide from the Avenue C to First Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Along the southern perimeter of Gramercy Park, between Gramercy Park East and Gramercy Park West, 20th Street is known as Gramercy Park South.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Between Second and Third Avenues, 21st Street is alternatively known as Police Officer Anthony Sanchez Way.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Along the northern perimeter of Gramercy Park, between Gramercy Park East and Gramercy Park West, 21st Street is known as Gramercy Park North.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 23rd Street is another main numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It begins at Avenue C/FDR Drive and ends at Eleventh Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Additionally, there is the M23 Select Bus Service, running through the length of 23rd Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] A small portion of 24th Street exists between First Avenue and East Midtown Plaza ending at a dead end before Second Avenue, a second portion is between East Midtown Plaza and Madison Avenue, ending because of Madison Square Park.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 25th Street, which is in three parts, starts at FDR Drive, is a pedestrian plaza between Third Avenue and Lexington Avenue, and ends at Madison.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Then West 24th and 25th streets continue from Fifth Avenue to Eleventh Avenue (25th) or Twelfth Avenue (24th).
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The two cul-de-sacs on 24th Street between First and Second avenues were created in the late 1960s to connect the northern and southern blocks of East Midtown Plaza with a mid-block pedestrian plaza having a focal point on St.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The pedestrian plaza on 25th Street between Third and Lexington avenues, named the "Clivner=Field Plaza", was completed in 2021 and provides outdoor space for the campus of Baruch College.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 26th Street is all in one part and after reaching FDR Drive bends and runs parallel to FDR Drive up to 30th Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Some of the most notable venues are Bungalow 8, Marquee, Suzie Wong, Cain, and Pink Elephant.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 27th and continuing down almost the entire rest of the block, the former warehouse spaces of clubs Twilo, Guesthouse, Home, Bed, and more have been repurposed by British immersive theater group Punchdrunk as The McKittrick Hotel, the site of their theatrical experience *Sleep No More*.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Heading east, 27th Street passes through Chelsea Park between Tenth and Ninth Avenues, with the Fashion Institute of Technology (FIT) on the corner of Eighth.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] On Madison Avenue between 26th and 27th streets, on the site of the old Madison Square Garden, is the New York Life Building, built in 1928 and designed by Cass Gilbert, with a square tower topped by a striking gilded pyramid.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Twenty-Seventh Street passes one block north of Madison Square Park and culminates at Bellevue Hospital on First Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The segment of 27th Street east of Second Avenue is a pedestrian mall and passes through Bellevue South Park.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 30th Street runs uninterrupted across the island from 12th Avenue to FDR Drive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It is the southern terminus of Dyer Avenue and thus also of the Lincoln Tunnel's eastern approach.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] There is also an elevator with access to the High Line on the West Side.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Tisch Hospital is bounded on the south by 30th Street between 1st Avenue and FDR Drive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The segment of 30th Street between First and Second avenues was widened by 20 feet (6.1 m) in the 1950s when the superblock for Kips Bay Towers was created.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] On the East Side, both streets end at Second Avenue, where the street grid is interrupted by superblocks containing Kips Bay Towers and NYU Medical Center.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Francis of Assisi is situated at 135–139 West 31st Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] At 210 West is the Capuchin Monastery of St.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] At the corner of Broadway and West 31st Street is the Grand Hotel.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The former Hotel Pierrepont was located at 43 West 32nd Street, The Continental NYC tower is at the corner of Sixth Avenue and 32nd Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 29 East 32nd Street was the location of the first building owned by the Grolier Club between 1890 and 1917.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] In 2017, the segment of 32nd Street between Second and Third avenues was co-named "Ms.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Magazine Way" in honor of the location where the publication was launched at 207 East 32nd Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 33rd Street runs uninterrupted from First Avenue to Seventh Avenue where it turns into a pedestrian road for a quarter of a block and turns back into a street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Then it runs the rest of the way to 12th Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the north side of Hudson Yards and the south side of the Empire State Building.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The segment of 33rd Street between First and Second avenues was widened by 20 feet (6.1 m) in the 1950s when the superblock for Kips Bay Towers was created.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] In 2018, the same street segment was converted from one-way to two-way traffic to improve access for ambulances traveling to emergency entrance of NYU Langone Health on First Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] At Park Avenue, 33rd Street was closed to westbound through traffic beginning in 1999, when barriers were installed at the southern end of the Park Avenue Tunnel.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] In 2019, the segment of 33rd Street between Tenth and Eleventh avenues was reconstructed as part of the Hudson Yards Redevelopment Project, which included raising the street elevation by up to 15 feet (4.6 m) for integration with Hudson Boulevard.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 35th Street runs from FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations include East River Ferry, Mercy University Manhattan Campus, and the Jacob K.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 36th Street runs from the FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the south side of the Queens–Midtown Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit and over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 36th Street are the American Copper Buildings, Sniffen Court, The Morgan Library & Museum, Gotham Hall, and the Javits Center.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 37th Street runs from the FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the north side of the Queens–Midtown Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit and over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 37th Street are the Corinthian, the Morgan Library & Museum, Gotham Hall, and the Javits Center.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 38th Street runs from FDR Drive to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It runs on the south side of the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Notable locations on 38th Street are The Corinthian, The Town House Hotel, 425 Fifth Avenue, and the Javits Center.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 39th Street runs from First Avenue to Eleventh Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It runs over the Lincoln Tunnel's Manhattan entrance/exit.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] A notable location on 39th Street is the Astro's Dog Run.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] A portion of West 46th Street between Eighth and Ninth Avenues is nicknamed **Restaurant Row**, after the number of restaurants located along its length.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Mayor John Lindsay had designated the street as Restaurant Row in 1973, honoring 16 restaurants on the block.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The Mount Vernon Hotel Museum, one of only eight surviving pre-1800 buildings in Manhattan, is located at 421 East 61st Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The Pierre, a luxury hotel opened in 1930, is at 2 East 61st Street, at the intersection with Fifth Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The Gateway School, an independent school for children aged 5 to 14 with learning disabilities, is located at 211 West 61st Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The Consulate-General of Russia in New York City was opened at 7–9 East 61st Street in 1933 and closed in 1948.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] East 77th and 78th streets run normally west of York Avenue, but east of York Avenue, 77th runs east, and 78th runs west, to accommodate the Pavilion at 500 East 77th.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The FDR Drive has an exit at 78th and an entrance at 79th.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] At the corner of 77th and York, on which sits PS 158, pedestrians cross 77th on red and wait on the green on the east side of York.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] As with all of Manhattan's numbered streets from 60th to 109th Street, 80th Street is divided by Central Park into eastern and western sections.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Traffic on 80th Street, on both sides of the park, runs west to east.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] West 80th Street begins at Riverside Drive on the Upper West Side, then passes West End Avenue, Broadway, and Amsterdam Avenue, then stops at Columbus Avenue when it reaches the grounds on the American Museum of Natural History.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Significant buildings on West 80th Street include those in the Riverside Drive–West 80th–81st Street Historic District, on both sides of the street's block between Riverside Drive and West End Avenue, such as the "Gothicesque" row houses at 307–317 West 80th Street designed by Charles H.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Israels, and those at 319–323 West 80th Street designed by Clarence F.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] True also designed the "vaguely Georgian" 328 West 80th Street on the same block, which also contains George F.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Pelham II's 411 West End Avenue, an Art Deco apartment building.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] East 80th Street begins at Fifth Avenue on the Upper East Side and continues past Madison, Park, Lexington, and Third, where it enters the section of the Upper East Side called Yorkville.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It then continues past Second, First, York and East End Avenues before dead-ending at the FDR Drive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Significant buildings on East 80th Street include the American Irish Historical Society at 991 Fifth Avenue; the houses of Franklyn and Edna Woolworth and her two sisters at 2, 4, and 6 East 80th Street, built by F.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Gilbert; the postmodern 45 East 80th Street at Madison Avenue, designed by Liebman Liebman & Associates; the raw concrete 1967 Manhattan Church of Christ by Eggers & Higgins; 52 East 80th Street between Madison and Park, built in the 1890s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Schmidt; and the same designer's Vincent and Helen Astor House at #130, built in 1927–28 and now the Junior League of the City of New York.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] At 1157 Lexington Avenue is the 1932 Unitarian Church of All Souls, designed by Robert Upjohn.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The first segment, West 90th Street begins at Riverside Drive and ends at Central Park West or West Drive, when it is open, in Central Park on the Upper West Side.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The second segment of East 90th Street begins at East Drive, at Engineers Gate of Central Park.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] When East Drive is closed, East 90th Street begins at Fifth Avenue on the Upper East Side and curves to the right at the FDR Drive becoming East End Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Our Lady of Good Counsel Church, is located on East 90th Street between Third Avenue and Second Avenue, across the street from Ruppert Towers (1601 and 1619 Third Avenue) and Ruppert Park.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Asphalt Green is a nonprofit community center dedicated to sports, fitness, and wellness located on East 90th Street between York Avenue and East End Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Above 114th Street between Amsterdam Avenue and Morningside Drive, there is a private indoor pedestrian bridge connecting two buildings on the campus of Mount Sinai Morningside.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 17 East 126th Street was the location of Art Kane's 1958 photograph of contemporary jazz musicians, now known as *A Great Day in Harlem*, which featured in the 2004 Steven Spielberg film *The Terminal*.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The 132nd Street Community Garden is located on 132nd Street between Adam Clayton Powell Jr.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] In 1997, the lot received a garden makeover; the Borough President's office funded the installation of a $100,000 water distribution system that keeps the wide variety of trees green.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The garden also holds a goldfish pond and several benches.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The spirit of the neighborhood lives in gardens like this one, planted and tended by local residents.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The Manhattanville Bus Depot (formerly known as the **132nd Street Bus Depot**) is located on West 132nd and 133rd Street between Broadway and Riverside Drive in the Manhattanville neighborhood.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 155th Street starts on the West Side at Riverside Drive, crossing Broadway, Amsterdam Avenue and St.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Nicholas Place, the terrain drops off steeply, and 155th Street is carried on a 1,600-foot (490 m) long viaduct, a City Landmark constructed in 1893, that slopes down towards the Harlem River, continuing onto the Macombs Dam Bridge, crossing over (but not intersecting with) the Harlem River Drive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] A separate, unconnected section of 155th Street runs under the viaduct, connecting Bradhurst Avenue and the Harlem River Drive.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The New York City Subway serves 155th Street on the IND Eighth Avenue and Concourse Lines.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] West of Fort Washington Avenue, 181st Street is largely residential, bordering Hudson Heights and having a few shops to serve the local residents.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] East of Fort Washington Avenue, the street becomes increasingly commercial, becoming dominated entirely by retail stores where the street reaches Broadway and continues as such until reaching the Harlem River.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It is the area's major shopping district.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 181st Street is served by two New York City Subway lines; there is a 181st Street station at Fort Washington Avenue on the IND Eighth Avenue Line (A train) and a 181st Street station at St.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Nicholas Avenue on the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line (1 train).
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The stations are about 500 metres (550 yd) from each other and are not connected.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The George Washington Bridge Bus Terminal is a couple of blocks south on Fort Washington Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 181st Street is also the last south/west exit in New York on the Trans-Manhattan Expressway (I-95), just before crossing the George Washington Bridge to New Jersey.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 187th Street intersects with, from east to west, Laurel Hill Terrace, Amsterdam Avenue, Audubon Avenue, St.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Nicholas Avenue, Wadsworth Avenue, Broadway, Bennett Avenue, Overlook Terrace, Fort Washington Avenue, Pinehurst Avenue, Cabrini Boulevard and Chittenden Avenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The many institutions on 187th Street include Mount Sinai Jewish Center, the Dombrov Shtiebel, and the uptown campus of Yeshiva University.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The local public elementary and middle school P.S./M.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 187 is located on Cabrini Boulevard, just north of 187th Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The Dyckman Street station was formerly called "Dyckman Street–200th Street", but there has never been a street in Manhattan with that number.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] A 196th street does exist, between Broadway and Ellwood Street.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] It is the only street between what would be 193rd and 201st to have numbered signage.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The University Heights Bridge, a swing bridge across the Harlem River, connects the street with Fordham Road in the Bronx.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] While 208th Street exists as a small driveway and parking lot located just south of the 207th Street Yard, Manhattan has no streets numbered 209th or 210th.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Manhattan has no streets numbered 221st, 222nd, 223rd, or 224th, as their theoretical location is taken up by the Spuyten Duyvil Creek.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] Despite having streets numbered 225th, 227th and 228th in the Marble Hill neighborhood, Manhattan has no street numbered 226th.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] 228th Street, located in the Marble Hill neighborhood, is the highest numbered street in Manhattan.
[src:andrew-carnegie/91st-street-manhattan] The street numbers continue in The Bronx.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was born in Tehran to an aristocratic family.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] At the age of eight, his father was imprisoned during a government crackdown on the Bábí Faith and the family's possessions were looted, leaving them in virtual poverty.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His father was exiled from their native Iran, and the family established their residence in Baghdad in Iraq, where they stayed for ten years.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] They were later called by the Ottoman state to Istanbul before entering another period of confinement in Edirne and finally the prison-city of ʻAkká (Acre). ʻAbdu'l-Bahá remained a prisoner there until the Young Turk Revolution freed him in 1908 at the age of 64.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He then made several journeys to the West to spread the Baháʼí message beyond its middle-eastern roots, but the onset of World War I left him largely confined to Haifa from 1914 to 1918.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Following the war, the openly hostile Ottoman authorities were replaced by the British Mandate over Palestine, during which time he was appointed a Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire for his help in averting famine following the war.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In 1892, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was appointed in his father's will to be his successor and head of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His *Tablets of the Divine Plan* galvanized Baháʼís in North America to spread the Baháʼí teachings to new territories, and his Will and Testament laid the foundation for the current Baháʼí administrative order.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Many of his writings, prayers and letters are extant, and his discourses with the Western Baháʼís emphasize the growth of the religion by the late 1890s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Depending on context, he would have gone by either Mírzá ʻAbbás (Persian) or ʻAbbás Effendi (Turkish), both of which are equivalent to the English Sir ʻAbbás.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During most of his time as head of the Bahá'í Faith, he used and preferred the title of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá ("servant of Bahá", a reference to his father).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He is commonly referred to in Baháʼí texts as "The Master".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was born in Tehran, Persia (now Iran) on 23 May 1844 (5th of Jamadiyu'l-Avval, 1260 AH), the eldest son of Baháʼu'lláh and Navváb.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was born on the same night on which the Báb declared his mission.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Given the name ʻAbbás at birth, he was named after his grandfather Mírzá ʻAbbás Núrí, a prominent and powerful nobleman. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá's early years were shaped by his father's prominent role within the Bábí community.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] As a child, he fondly recalled interactions with the Bábí, Táhirih, describing how she would take him on her knee, caress him, and engage in heartfelt conversations, leaving a lasting impression on him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His childhood was characterized by happiness and carefree moments.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The family's residences in Tehran and the countryside were not only comfortable but also beautifully adorned.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Alongside his younger siblings – a sister, Bahíyyih, and a brother, Mihdí – he experienced a life of privilege, joy, and comfort. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá loved playing in the gardens with his younger sister, fostering a strong bond between them.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During his formative years, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá observed his parents' commitment to various charitable endeavors, including the conversion of part of their home into a hospital ward for women and children.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Due to a life largely marked by exile and imprisonment, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá had limited opportunities for formal schooling.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In his youth, it was customary for children of nobility, including ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, not to attend conventional schools.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Instead, noblemen typically received a brief education at home, focusing on subjects such as scripture, rhetoric, calligraphy, and basic mathematics, with an emphasis on preparing for life within royal courts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá spent only a short period at a traditional preparatory school at the age of seven for a single year.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His mother and uncle took on the responsibility of his early education, but the primary source of his learning was his father.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] According to contemporary accounts ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was an eloquent and charming child.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] At the age of seven, he faced a severe health challenge when he contracted tuberculosis, and his prognosis suggested death.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Though the illness abated, this marked the beginning of a lifelong struggle with recurrent bouts of various illnesses that would persist throughout his life.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He described how "I saw a dark, steep place.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] We entered a small, narrow doorway, and went down two steps, but beyond those one could see nothing.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In the middle of the stairway, all of a sudden we heard His [Baháʼu'lláh's]…voice: 'Do not bring him in here', and so they took me back".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Baháʼu'lláh was eventually released from prison but was ordered into exile, and ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, then eight years old, joined his father on the journey to Baghdad in the winter (January to April) of 1853.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During the journey ʻAbdu'l-Bahá suffered from frost-bite.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In 1856, news of an ascetic engaging in discourses with local Súfí leaders reached family and friends, raising hopes that it could be Bahá’u’lláh.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Immediately, they went to search for Baháʼu'lláh, and in March, brought him back to Baghdad.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] On seeing his father, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá fell to his knees and wept loudly "Why did you leave us?", and his mother and sister did the same. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá soon became his father's secretary and shield.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During the sojourn in the city ʻAbdu'l-Bahá grew from a boy into a young man.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was noted as a "remarkably fine looking youth", and remembered for his charity.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Having passed the age of maturity, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was regularly seen in the mosques of Baghdad discussing religious topics and the scripture as a young man.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In 1863, in what became known as the Garden of Ridván, his father Baháʼu'lláh announced to a few companions that he was the manifestation of God and He whom God shall make manifest whose coming had been foretold by the Báb.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] On day eight of the twelve days, it is reported that ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was the first person to whom Baháʼu'lláh revealed his claim.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In 1863, Baháʼu'lláh was summoned to Istanbul, and thus his family, including ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, then eighteen, accompanied him on his 110-day journey.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The journey to Constantinople was another wearisome voyage, and ʻAbdu'l-Bahá helped feed the exiles.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] It was here that his position became more prominent amongst the Baháʼís.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] This was further solidified by Baháʼu'lláh's tablet of the Branch in which he constantly exalts his son's virtues and station.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Bahá’u’lláh and his family were soon exiled to Adrianople, and on this journey ʻAbdu'l-Bahá again suffered from frostbite.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In Adrianople ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was regarded as the sole comforter of his family – in particular to his mother.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] At this point ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was known by the Baháʼís as "the Master", and by non-Baháʼís as ʻAbbás Effendi ("Effendi" signifies "Sir").
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] It was in Adrianople that Baháʼu'lláh referred to his son as "the Mystery of God".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The title of "Mystery of God" symbolises, according to Baháʼís, that ʻAbdu'l-Bahá is not a manifestation of God but that in the "person of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá the incompatible characteristics of a human nature and superhuman knowledge and perfection have been blended and are completely harmonized".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Baháʼu'lláh gave his son many other titles such as *G͟husn-i-Aʻzam* (meaning "Mightiest Branch" or "Mightier Branch"), the "Branch of Holiness", "the Center of the Covenant" and the apple of his eye.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Upon learning of yet another exile of Bahá’u’llah, this time to Palestine, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá ("the Master") was devastated when hearing the news that he and his family were to be exiled separately from Baháʼu'lláh.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] It was, according to Baháʼís, through his intercession that the idea was reverted and the rest of the family were allowed to be exiled together.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] At the age of 24, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was clearly chief-steward to his father and an outstanding member of the Baháʼí community.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In 1868 Baháʼu'lláh and his family were exiled to the penal colony of ʻAkká, Palestine where it was expected that the family would perish.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Arrival in ʻAkká was distressing for the family and exiles when they were met by a hostile local population.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] When told that the women were to sit on the shoulders of the men to reach the shore, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá obtained chairs to carry the women to land.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His sister and father fell dangerously ill. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was able to procure some anesthetic and nursed the sick.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The Baháʼís were imprisoned under horrendous conditions in a cluster of cells covered in excrement and dirt. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá himself fell dangerously ill with dysentery, and a sympathetic soldier permitted a physician to attend to him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The population shunned them, the soldiers treated them badly, and the behaviour of Siyyid Muhammad-i-Isfahani (an Azali) aggravated matters.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Morale declined further with the accidental death of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá's youngest brother Mírzá Mihdí at the age of 22.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The grieving ʻAbdu'l-Bahá kept a night-long vigil beside his brother's body.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Over time, he gradually assumed responsibility for the relationships between the small Baháʼí exile community and the outside world.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] It was through his interaction with the people of ʻAkká (Acre) that, they recognized the innocence of the Baháʼís, and thus the conditions of imprisonment were eased.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Four months after the death of Mihdí the family moved from the prison to the House of ʻAbbúd.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Gradually the respect of the local population for the Baháʼís increased, and in particular, for ʻAbdu'l-Bahá who soon became very popular in the penal colony.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Myron Henry Phelps a wealthy New York lawyer described how "a crowd of human beings...Syrians, Arabs, Ethiopians, and many others", all waited to talk and receive ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] With the passage of time ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was able to rent alternative accommodations for the family, and eventually the family moved to the Mansion of Bahjí around 1879 when an epidemic caused its residents to flee.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá undertook a history of the Bábí religion through publication of A Traveller's Narrative (Makála-i-Shakhsí Sayyáh) in 1886, later translated and published in translation in 1891 through Cambridge University through the agency of Edward Granville Browne.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] When ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was a young man, speculation was rife amongst the Baháʼís as to whom he would marry.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Several young girls were seen as marriage prospects but ʻAbdu'l-Bahá seemed disinclined to marriage.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] On 8 March 1873, at the urging of his father, the twenty-eight-year-old ʻAbdu'l-Bahá married Fátimih Nahrí of Isfahán (1847–1938) a twenty-five-year-old from an upper-class family of the city.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Her father was Mírzá Muḥammad ʻAlí Nahrí of Isfahan, an eminent Baháʼí with prominent connections.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Fátimih was brought from Persia to ʻAkká after both Baháʼu'lláh and his wife Navváb expressed an interest that she marries ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] After a wearisome journey from Isfahán to Akka she finally arrived accompanied by her brother in 1872.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The young couple were betrothed for about five months before the marriage itself commenced.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In the meantime, Fátimih lived in the home of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá's uncle Mírzá Músá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] According to her later memoirs, Fátimih fell in love with ʻAbdu'l-Bahá on seeing him. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá himself had shown little inkling to marriage until meeting Fátimih; who was entitled Munírih by Baháʼu'lláh.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The first born was a son Mihdí Effendi who died aged about 3.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was followed by Ḍíyáʼíyyih K͟hánum, Fuʼádíyyih K͟hánum (who dies very young), Rúhangíz Khánum (d.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] 1887 aged 5), Túbá K͟hánum, Rúhá K͟hánum (mother of Munib Shahid), and Munnavar K͟hánum.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The death of his children caused ʻAbdu'l-Bahá immense grief – in particular the death of his son Husayn Effendi came at a difficult time following the death of his mother and uncle.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The surviving children (all daughters) were; Ḍíyáʼíyyih K͟hánum (mother of Shoghi Effendi) (d.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Baháʼu'lláh wished that the Baháʼís follow the example of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá and gradually move away from polygamy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The marriage of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá to one woman and his choice to remain monogamous, from advice of his father and his own wish, legitimised the practice of monogamy to a people who hitherto had regarded polygamy as a righteous way of life.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] After Baháʼu'lláh died on 29 May 1892, the Book of the Covenant of Baháʼu'lláh (his will) named ʻAbdu'l-Bahá as Centre of the Covenant, successor and interpreter of Baháʼu'lláh's writings.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In Baháʼu'lláh's will, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá's half-brother, Muhammad ʻAlí, was mentioned by name as being subordinate to ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Muhammad ʻAlí became jealous of ‘Abdu’l-Bahá and set out to establish authority for himself as an alternative leader with the support of his brothers Badi’u'llah and Ḍíyáʼu'llah.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He began correspondence with Baháʼís in Iran, initially in secret, casting doubts in others' minds about ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] While most Baháʼís followed ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, a handful followed Muhammad ʻAlí including such prominent Bahá’ís as Mirza Javad and Ibrahim George Kheiralla, an early Baháʼí missionary to America.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Muhammad ʻAlí and Mirza Javad began to openly accuse ʻAbdu'l-Bahá of assuming too much authority, suggesting that he believed himself to be a Manifestation of God, equal in status to Baháʼu'lláh.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] With the exception of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá and Shoghi Effendi, Muhammad ʻAlí was supported by all of the remaining male relatives of Baháʼu'lláh, including Shoghi Effendi's father, Mírzá Hádí Shírází.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] However**,** in general the Bahá’ís experienced very little effect from the propaganda ofMuhammad ʻAlí and his allies; in the ʻAkká area, the followers of Muhammad ʻAlí represented six families at most, had no common religious activities, and were almost wholly assimilated into Muslim society.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Religions in the past faced schism and doctrinal drift after the death of their prophet founders. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá however managed to preserve the unity and doctrinal integrity of the Baháʼí Faith, even in the face of serious threats from his half-brother's opposition.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His success is especially notable given that even in the midst of these attacks his leadership brought about considerable expansion of the Baháʼí community beyond its initial cultural and geographic roots.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] By the end of 1898, Western pilgrims started traveling to Akka on pilgrimage to visit ʻAbdu'l-Bahá; this group of pilgrims, including Phoebe Hearst, was the first time that Baháʼís raised up in the West had met ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The first group arrived in 1898 and throughout late 1898 to early 1899 Western Baháʼís sporadically visited ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The group was relatively young containing mainly women from high American society in their 20s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The group of Westerners aroused suspicion for the authorities, and consequently ʻAbdu'l-Bahá's confinement was tightened.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] It was Laura Clifford Barney who, by asking questions of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá over many years and many visits to Haifa, compiled what later became the book Some Answered Questions.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During the final years of the 19th century, while ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was still officially a prisoner and confined to ʻAkka, he organized the transfer of the remains of the Báb from Iran to Palestine.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He then organized the purchase of land on Mount Carmel that Baháʼu'lláh had instructed should be used to lay the remains of the Báb, and organized for the construction of the Shrine of the Báb.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] With the increase of pilgrims visiting ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, Muhammad ʻAlí conspired with the Ottoman authorities to re-introduce stricter terms on ʻAbdu'l-Bahá's imprisonment in August 1901.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] By 1902, however, due to the support of the Governor of ʻAkka, the situation was greatly eased; while pilgrims were able to once again visit ʻAbdu'l-Bahá, he was still confined to the city.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In February 1903, two followers of Muhammad ʻAlí, including Badiʻu'llah and Siyyid ʻAliy-i-Afnan, broke with Muhammad ʻAli and wrote books and letters giving details of Muhammad ʻAli's plots and noting that what was circulating about ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was fabrication.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In his role as head of the Bahá’í Faith, ‘Abdu’l-Bahá would occasionally communicate with leaders of thought to offer commentary and guidance based on the Bahá’í teachings, and in defense of the Bahá’í community.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During this period, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá communicated with a number of Young Turks, who sought to reform to the reign of Sultan Abdul Hamid II, including Namık Kemal, Ziya Pasha and Midhat Pasha.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He emphasized Baháʼís "seek freedom and love liberty, hope for equality, are well-wishers of humanity and ready to sacrifice their lives to unite humanity" but on a more broad approach than the Young Turks.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Abdullah Cevdet, one of the founders of the Committee of Union and Progress who considered the Baháʼí Faith an intermediary step between Islam and the ultimate abandonment of religious belief, would go on trial for defense of Baháʼís in a periodical he founded.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ‛Abdu'l-Bahá also had contact with military leaders, including such individuals as Bursalı Mehmet Tahir Bey and Hasan Bedreddin.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The latter, who in an earlier period was involved in the overthrow of Sultan Abdülaziz in 1876, is commonly known as Bedri Paşa or Bedri Pasha and is referred to in Persian Baháʼí sources as Bedri Bey (Badri Beg).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He probably came to know ‘Abdu’l-Baha around 1898 when he served in the Ottoman administration in Akká.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Persian sources cite him was a Baháʼí and he who translated ‛Abdu'l-Baha's works into French. ‘Abdu’l-Bahá continued to communicate with him for several years when he was governor of Albania.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá also met Muhammad Abduh, one of the key figures of Islamic Modernism and the Salafi movement, in Beirut, at a time when the two men shared similar goals of religious reform.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Rashid Rida asserts that during his visits to Beirut, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá would attend Abduh's study sessions.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Due to Muhammad ʻAli's accusations against him, a Commission of Inquiry interviewed ʻAbdu'l-Bahá in 1905, almost resulting in exile to Fezzan.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In response, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá wrote the sultan a letter protesting that his followers refrain from involvement in partisan politics and that his *tariqa* had guided many Americans to Islam.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The next few years in ʻAkka were relatively free of pressures and pilgrims were able to come and visit ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] By 1909 the mausoleum of the Shrine of the Báb was completed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The 1908 Young Turks revolution liberated all political and religious prisoners in the Ottoman Empire, and ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was freed from imprisonment.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His first action after his liberation was to visit the Shrine of Baháʼu'lláh in Bahji.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] While ʻAbdu'l-Bahá continued to live in ʻAkka immediately following the revolution, he soon moved to live in Haifa near the Shrine of the Báb.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In 1910, with the freedom to leave the country, he embarked on a three-year journey to Egypt, Europe, and North America, spreading the Baháʼí message.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] From August to December 1911, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá visited cities in Europe, including London, Bristol, and Paris.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The purpose of these trips was to support the Baháʼí communities in the west and to further spread his father's teachings.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In the following year, he undertook a much more extensive journey to the United States and Canada to once again spread his father's teachings.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He arrived in New York City on 11 April 1912, after declining an offer of passage on the RMS *Titanic*, telling the Baháʼí believers, instead, to "Donate this to charity." He instead travelled on a slower craft, the RMS *Cedric*, and cited preference of a longer sea journey as the reason.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] After hearing of the Titanic's sinking on 16 April he was quoted as saying "I was asked to sail upon the Titanic, but my heart did not prompt me to do so." While he spent most of his time in New York, he visited Chicago, Cleveland, Pittsburgh, Washington, D.C.,Boston and Philadelphia.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In August of the same year he started a more extensive journey to places including New Hampshire, the Green Acre school in Maine, and Montreal (his only visit to Canada).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He then travelled west to Minneapolis, Minnesota; San Francisco; Stanford; and Los Angeles, California before returning east at the end of October.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] On 5 December 1912 he set sail back to Europe.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During his visit to North America he visited many missions, churches, and groups, as well as having scores of meetings in homes of Baháʼís, and offering innumerable personal meetings with hundreds of people.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During his talks he proclaimed Baháʼí principles such as the unity of God, unity of the religions, oneness of humanity, equality of women and men, world peace and economic justice.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He also insisted that all his meetings be open to all races.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His visit and talks were the subject of hundreds of newspaper articles.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His 1912 visit to Montreal also inspired humourist Stephen Leacock to parody him in his bestselling 1914 book *Arcadian Adventures with the Idle Rich*.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In Chicago one newspaper headline included "His Holiness Visits Us, Not Pius X but A.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Baha," and ʻAbdu'l-Bahá's visit to California was reported in the *Palo Altan*.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Back in Europe, he visited London, Edinburgh, Paris (where he stayed for two months), Stuttgart, Budapest, and Vienna.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Finally, on 12 June 1913, he returned to Egypt, where he stayed for six months before returning to Haifa.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During World War I (1914–1918) ʻAbdu'l-Bahá stayed in Palestine and was unable to travel.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He carried on a limited correspondence, which included the *Tablets of the Divine Plan*, a collection of fourteen letters addressed to the Baháʼís of North America, later described as one of three "charters" of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The letters assign a leadership role for the North American Baháʼís in spreading the religion around the planet.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Haifa was under real threat of Allied bombardment, enough that ʻAbdu'l-Bahá and other Baháʼís temporarily retreated to the hills east of ʻAkka.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was also under threats from Cemal Paşa, the Ottoman military chief who at one point expressed his desire to crucify him and destroy Baháʼí properties in Palestine.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The swift Megiddo offensive of the British General Allenby swept away the Turkish forces in Palestine before harm was done to the Baháʼís, and the war was over less than two months later.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The conclusion of World War I led to the openly hostile Ottoman authorities being replaced by the more friendly British Mandate, allowing for a renewal of correspondence, pilgrims, and development of the Baháʼí World Centre properties.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] It was during this revival of activity that the Baháʼí Faith saw an expansion and consolidation in places like Egypt, the Caucasus, Iran, Turkmenistan, North America and South Asia under the leadership of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The end of the war brought about several political developments on which ʻAbdu'l-Bahá commented.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He also said that it was "incapable of establishing Universal Peace" because it did not represent all nations and had only trivial power over its member states.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Around the same time, the British Mandate supported the ongoing immigration of Jews to Palestine. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá mentioned the immigration as a fulfillment of prophecy, and encouraged the Zionists to develop the land and "elevate the country for all its inhabitants...
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] They must not work to separate the Jews from the other Palestinians...If the Zionists will mingle with the other races and live in unity with them, they will succeed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In 1901, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá had purchased about 1704 acres of scrubland near the Jordan river and by 1907 many Baháʼís from Iran had begun sharecropping on the land. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá received between 20 and 33% of their harvest (or cash equivalent), which was shipped to Haifa.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] With the war still raging in 1917, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá received a large amount of wheat from the crops, and also bought other available wheat and shipped it back to Haifa.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The wheat arrived just after the British captured Palestine, and as such was widely distributed to allay the famine.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] For this service in averting a famine in Northern Palestine he received the honour of Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire at a ceremony held in his honor at the home of the British Governor on 27 April 1920.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was later visited by General Allenby, King Faisal (later King of Iraq), Herbert Samuel (High Commissioner for Palestine), and Ronald Storrs (Military Governor of Jerusalem).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá died on Monday, 28 November 1921, sometime after 1:15 a.m.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Then Colonial Secretary Winston Churchill telegraphed the High Commissioner for Palestine, "convey to the Baháʼí Community, on behalf of His Majesty's Government, their sympathy and condolence." Similar messages came from Viscount Allenby, the Council of Ministers of Iraq, and others.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was buried in the front room of the Shrine of the Báb on Mount Carmel.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His interment there is meant to be temporary, until his own mausoleum can be built in the vicinity of Riḍván Garden, known as the Shrine of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá left a *Will and Testament* that was originally written between 1901 and 1908 and addressed to Shoghi Effendi, who at that time was only 4–11 years old.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The will appoints Shoghi Effendi as the first in a line of Guardians of the religion, a hereditary executive role that may provide authoritative interpretations of scripture. ʻAbdu'l-Bahá directed all Baháʼís to turn to him and obey him, and assured him of divine protection and guidance.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The will also provided a formal reiteration of his teachings, such as the instructions to teach, manifest spiritual qualities, associate with all people, and shun Covenant-breakers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Many obligations of the Universal House of Justice and the Hands of the Cause were also elaborated.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Shoghi Effendi later described the document as one of three "charters" of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The authenticity and provisions of the will were almost universally accepted by Baháʼís around the world, with the exception of Ruth White and a few other Americans who tried to protest Shoghi Effendi's leadership.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] In volumes of *The Baháʼí World* published in 1930 and 1933, Shoghi Effendi named nineteen Baháʼís as disciples of ʻAbdu'l-Bahá and heralds of the Covenant, including Thornton Chase, Hippolyte Dreyfus-Barney, John Esslemont, Lua Getsinger, and Robert Turner.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] No other statements about them have been found in Shoghi Effendi's writings.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] During his lifetime there was some ambiguity among Baháʼís as to his station relative to Baháʼu'lláh, and later to Shoghi Effendi.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Some American newspapers erroneously reported him to be a Baháʼí prophet or the return of Christ.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Shoghi Effendi later formalized his legacy as the last of three "Central Figures" of the Baháʼí Faith and the "Perfect exemplar" of the teachings, also claiming that holding him on an equal status to Baháʼu'lláh or Jesus was heretical.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Shoghi Effendi also wrote that during the anticipated Baháʼí dispensation of 1000 years there will be no equal to ʻAbdu'l-Bahá.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was described as handsome, and bore striking resemblance to his mother.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] As an adult he reached medium height but he gave the impression of being taller.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He had dark hair that flowed to his shoulders, grey coloured eyes, a fair complexion and an aquiline nose.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] After the death of Bahá’u’lláh, ʻAbdu'l-Bahá began to visibly age.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] By the late 1890s his hair had turned snow-white and deep lines set on his face.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] As a young man he was athletic and enjoyed archery, horseback riding and swimming.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Even later in his life ʻAbdu'l-Bahá remained active going for long walks in Haifa and Acre.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was a major presence for the Bahá’ís during his lifetime, and he continues to influence the Bahá’í community today.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Bahá’ís regard ‘Abdu’l-Bahá as the perfect example of the teachings of his father and therefore strive to emulate him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Anecdotes about him are frequently used to illustrate particular points about morality and interpersonal relations.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was remembered for his charisma, compassion, philanthropy and strength in the face of suffering.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Even ardent enemies of the Bahá’í Faith were on occasion taken by meeting him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Mírzá 'Abdu'l-Muḥammad Írání Mu'addibu's-Sulṭán, an Iranian, and Shaykh 'Alí Yúsuf, an Arab, were both newspaper editors in Egypt who had published harsh attacks on the Bahá’í Faith in their papers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] They called on ‘Abdu’l-Bahá when he was in Egypt and their attitude changed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Bixby, who was the author of a hostile article on the Bahá’í Faith in the United States, felt compelled to witness Abdu'l-Bahá's personal qualities.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The effect of ‘Abdu’l-Bahá on those who were already committed Bahá’ís was greater still.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ʻAbdu'l-Bahá was widely known for his encounters with the poor and dying.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His generosity resulted in his own family complaining that they were left with nothing.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was sensitive to people’s feelings, and later expressed his wish to be a beloved figure of the Bahá’ís saying “I am your father...and you must be glad and rejoice, for I love you exceedingly.” According to historical accounts, he had a keen sense of humour and was relaxed and informal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was open about personal tragedies such as the loss of his children and the sufferings he'd endured as a prisoner, further enhancing his popularity.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] ‘Abdu’l-Bahá directed the affairs of the Bahá’í community with care.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He was inclined to allow a large range of personal interpretations of the Bahá’í teachings as long as these did not obviously contradict fundamental principles.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He did, however, expel members of the religion he felt were challenging his leadership and deliberately causing disunity in the community.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] Outbreaks of persecution of the Bahá’ís affected him deeply.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] He wrote personally to the families of those who had been martyred.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The total estimated number of tablets that ʻAbdu'l-Bahá wrote are over 27,000 of which only a fraction have been translated into English.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] His works fall into two groups including first his direct writings and second his lectures and speeches as noted by others.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abdu-l-bahá] The *Secret of Divine Civilization* and the *Sermon on the Art of Governance* were widely circulated anonymously.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:andrew-carnegie/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:andrew-carnegie/andrew-carnegie-p01] He became a leading philanthropist in the United States, Great Britain, and the British Empire.
